Part A ‚Äì Basics & Concepts

1. What is SharePoint?

SharePoint is a web-based collaboration platform by Microsoft that allows organizations to store, organize, share, and access information securely from any device.

2. Difference between SharePoint Online and On-Premises

Online: Cloud-based, subscription, automatic updates.

On-Premises: Installed on local servers, manual updates, full control.


3. What are SharePoint Sites?

Team Site: Collaboration-focused, integrates with Teams.

Communication Site: Broadcast information to large audiences.

Hub Site: Connects multiple sites, unified navigation and search.


4. What is a SharePoint List?

Structured collection of data items, similar to a database table.

5. What is a Document Library?

Special list designed to store documents with version control.

6. What is a Content Type?

A reusable set of columns, templates, and workflows applied across lists and libraries.

7. What is Managed Metadata?

Hierarchical classification of data using term sets, ensuring consistent metadata across sites.

8. What are SharePoint Groups?

Collections of users with defined permission levels (Owners, Members, Visitors).

9. Difference between Permissions and Groups

Permissions: Level of access (Read, Edit, Full Control)

Groups: Collection of users assigned specific permissions.


10. What is a Site Collection?

A container for multiple sites with shared top-level site, permissions, and settings.

11. What is the Recycle Bin in SharePoint Online?

Stage 1: 93 days for user restore

Stage 2: Additional 93 days, admin can restore


12. What is Versioning?

Tracks document changes. Supports major (1.0, 2.0) and minor (1.1, 1.2) versions.

13. What is a Lookup Column?

Connects a list column to another list to avoid duplicate entries.

14. What are Site Templates?

Predefined site designs for quick site creation.

15. Difference between Classic and Modern Pages

Classic: Legacy, server-side code

Modern: Responsive, mobile-friendly, client-side code, SPFx

Part B ‚Äì Intermediate Concepts

16. What are Views in SharePoint Lists?

Custom representations of data using filters, sorting, grouping, and formatting.

17. What is JSON Column Formatting?

Customizes UI of SharePoint columns (colors, icons, badges).

18. What is SharePoint Workflow?

Automated sequence of actions triggered by list events.

19. What is SharePoint SPFx?

Modern client-side development framework using React, TypeScript, and Node.js.

20. What is Power Automate Integration?

Automates workflows for SharePoint events like item creation, modification, or deletion.

21. What is a Hub Site?

Central site connecting multiple sites for navigation, search, and branding.

22. What is a Term Store?

Central hub for hierarchical metadata classification.

23. What is Site Script & Site Design?

Site Script: JSON defining site actions (lists, nav, theme)

Site Design: Applied configuration using Site Script


24. What is Retention Policy?

Keeps or deletes content automatically for compliance purposes.

25. What is a Sensitivity Label?

Classifies content for security, encryption, and external sharing control.

Part C ‚Äì Admin & Governance

26. SharePoint Admin Center Sections

Active Sites

Content Services

Sharing Settings

Access Control

Settings

Migration Manager

Term Store


27. How to manage external sharing?

Tenant-level & site-level settings

Domain allow/block lists

Link expiration & password protection


28. How to monitor usage?

Admin Center reports

PowerShell Get-SPOSite

OneDrive/SharePoint activity reports


29. How to handle storage quotas?

Tenant-level storage

Site-level quotas

Auto-expanding storage

Archive old content


30. How to restore deleted sites/files?

Active sites ‚Üí Deleted sites ‚Üí Restore

Up to 30 days for site restore

File/library restore via versioning or recycle bin


31. Permission Best Practices

Use groups, not individual users

Apply least-privilege model

Break inheritance only when needed

Regularly audit permissions


32. Governance Tips

Naming conventions

Hub sites usage

Retention policies enforcement

Avoid site sprawl

Monitor and archive old content



---

Part D ‚Äì PowerApps + SharePoint

33. How to connect PowerApps to SharePoint?

Use Canvas Apps or Model-Driven Apps

Customize SharePoint list forms

Enable CRUD operations


34. Customizing SharePoint Form in PowerApps

Open list ‚Üí Integrate ‚Üí PowerApps ‚Üí Customize Form

Add conditional visibility, role-based controls, and validation


35. Delegation in PowerApps

Use delegable functions (Filter, Sort, StartsWith)

Avoid non-delegable functions (Contains)

Index columns for large lists


36. PowerApps Patch Function

Used to create/update list items:

Patch(
    'Requests',
    Defaults('Requests'),
    {Title: txtTitle.Text, Status: "Pending"}
)

37. Handling Attachments

Use Attachment control

MaxAttachments property to limit

Supports Add/Remove/Download


38. Galleries and Data Tables

Show list items

Filter, sort, search

Connect multiple lists via collections


39. Role-Based Access

Load user roles via Office365Users.MyProfileV2()

Conditional visibility with If statements


40. Offline Mode

Store data in Collections

Sync back when online

Part E ‚Äì Power Automate + SharePoint

41. Common Triggers

When item is created

When item is modified

When a file is created/deleted


42. Common Actions

Create/Update/Delete items

Send email/notifications

Copy/Move files

Start approval flows


43. Approval Flows

Serial/Parallel approvals

Manager approval

Multi-stage workflows

Update item based on approval outcome


44. Document Automation

Auto-move based on metadata

