PART 13 ‚Äî SharePoint Developer & Customization Advanced Concepts

13.1 SharePoint Framework (SPFx) Overview

1. What is SPFx?
Modern client-side development framework
Supports React, Angular, Vue, or no framework
Runs in context of SharePoint Online or On-Premises (2016+)

2. Key Features
Client-side rendering
Supports modern UI and responsive design
Easy integration with Microsoft Graph and REST API
Package deployment via App Catalog

3. SPFx Project Types
Web Parts: UI components embedded in pages
Extensions: Application Customizers, Field Customizers, Command Sets
Library Components: Reusable code for multiple web parts

13.2 Setting up SPFx Development Environment

1. Prerequisites
Node.js (LTS version)
Yeoman & Gulp (npm install -g yo gulp)
SPFx Generator (npm install -g @microsoft/generator-sharepoint)
Visual Studio Code

2. Create SPFx Project
yo @microsoft/sharepoint
Choose project type, framework, and solution structure

3. Local Workbench
Test web parts locally before deployment

4. Gulp Commands
gulp serve ‚Üí Run locally
gulp bundle --ship ‚Üí Prepare for production
gulp package-solution --ship ‚Üí Generate .sppkg

13.3 SPFx Web Part Development

1. React Web Parts
Modern UI with reusable React components
State management via hooks

2. Properties & Configuration
Configurable via Property Pane
Dynamic updates without page reload

3. Event Handling
Click, change, submit, etc.
Use TypeScript strongly typed events

4. REST API Integration
sp.web.lists.getByTitle("Tasks").items.get()
Fetch/update SharePoint list data

5. Graph API Integration
await graphClient.api('/me').get();
Access Teams, OneDrive, users, groups

13.4 SPFx Extensions

1. Application Customizers
Add custom header/footer
Add scripts across site collection

2. Field Customizers
Change UI of list columns (icons, badges, colors)

3. Command Sets
Custom buttons on list/library toolbar
Trigger actions like Power Automate flow or custom API

13.5 Advanced SPFx Concepts

1. Deployment
Upload .sppkg to App Catalog
Tenant-wide deployment for all sites

2. API Permissions
Request Graph API or SharePoint permissions in package-solution.json
Admin approval required for elevated permissions

3. Component Reusability
Library components for shared UI or logic
Import across web parts

4. Performance Optimization
Lazy loading modules
Minimize HTTP calls
Use React memoization

5. Debugging
Browser developer tools
Console logging
SPFx logging libraries

13.6 PowerApps + SPFx Integration

1. Embed PowerApps Forms in SPFx Web Parts
Use iframe or web component
Conditional display based on permissions

2. SPFx Web Part as Data Source
Use REST/Graph API to push/pull data
PowerApps calls SPFx API for dynamic data

3. Custom APIs
SPFx + Azure Functions for complex business logic
Secure with Azure AD auth

13.7 Power Automate Integration

1. Trigger Flow from SPFx
Button click triggers Power Automate HTTP request
Pass list item or form data as JSON

2. Flow Responses
Capture results in SPFx for UI updates

3. Common Scenarios
Document approval, notifications, sync with external systems

13.8 Real-Time Developer Scenarios
1. Dashboard Web Part: Fetch data from multiple lists and display charts
2. Role-Based Access UI: Show/hide fields based on user group
3. Custom Column Formatting: SPFx Field Customizer for icon badges
4. Command Button Integration: Trigger Power Automate from list toolbar
5. Multi-List Data Merge: SPFx web part aggregates data across lists and libraries
6. Embed Teams Content: Web part fetches Teams messages or channels

13.9 SPFx Best Practices
Use TypeScript for type safety
Keep web parts small and reusable
Use environment variables for URLs
Optimize network calls (batch REST calls)
Always handle permissions gracefully

Part 14 ‚Äì SharePoint Backup, Recovery & Disaster Management

1. Site Collection Backup & Restore
On-Premises: Use PowerShell commands like Backup-SPSite and Restore-SPSite.
Backup-SPSite -Identity "https://contoso/sites/hr" -Path "C:\Backup\hr.bak"
Restore-SPSite -Identity "https://contoso/sites/hr" -Path "C:\Backup\hr.bak" -Force
Online: Use Site Recycle Bin for deleted sites (up to 93 days). For large-scale backup, use third-party tools like ShareGate.

2. OneDrive & Library Restore
Version History: Restore previous versions of files.
OneDrive Restore: Restore OneDrive to a previous state (up to 30 days).

3. Disaster Recovery Planning
Maintain backup schedule for site collections.
Use geo-redundancy if using SharePoint Online.
Test restore procedures regularly to ensure readiness.

4. Retention Policies
Apply retention labels to libraries or sites.
Automatically retain, archive, or delete content after a period.
Part 15 ‚Äì SharePoint Performance & Optimization

1. Handling Large Lists & Libraries
Lists with more than 5000 items require Indexed columns.
Use Filtered views to avoid threshold errors.

2. Caching & Content Delivery
Enable BLOB caching in On-Premises.
Use Office 365 CDN for static files (JS, CSS).

3. SPFx Optimization
Lazy-load components to improve page load.
Minimize bundle size using Webpack and code splitting.
Use React.memo or useCallback to reduce re-rendering.

4. PowerApps & Power Automate Performance
Reduce nested loops and avoid delegations beyond threshold.
Use Collections to cache data locally in PowerApps.

Part 16 ‚Äì SharePoint Migration & Hybrid Scenarios

1. Migration Tools
SPMT: Free Microsoft tool for migrating files, lists, and libraries.
ShareGate/Metalogix: Enterprise-grade migration with metadata, permissions, and workflows.

2. Hybrid SharePoint
Hybrid Search: Search both Online and On-Prem content.
Hybrid Sites: Seamless navigation and hub integration between On-Prem and Online.

3. Migration Considerations
File path length: Max 400 characters in SharePoint Online.
Restricted file types: .exe, .dll, .bat, etc.
Metadata and permissions mapping: Must match target environment.

4. Migration Steps
1. Inventory existing content.
2. Prepare source and target environments.
3. Map metadata, content types, and permissions.
4. Run test migration.
5. Execute full migration and validate results.

Part 17 ‚Äì SharePoint Business Intelligence & Reporting

1. Power BI Integration
Connect SharePoint lists and libraries.
Build dashboards with interactive visuals, slicers, and filters.

2. Excel Services & PivotTables
Analyze SharePoint data using Excel.
Publish Excel dashboards to SharePoint Online.

3. KPI Lists & Charts
Display key metrics using KPI web parts.
Track project milestones, targets, and achievements.

4. Embedded Reports in Teams
Embed SharePoint-hosted BI dashboards in Teams tabs.
Role-based security ensures proper access.

Part 18 ‚Äì SharePoint Security & Compliance

1. Data Loss Prevention (DLP)
Prevent sharing sensitive information outside organization.
Policies: Block, warn, or log sensitive info sharing.

2. Audit Logs
Track who accessed, edited, or deleted content.
Export logs for compliance (GDPR, HIPAA).

3. GDPR & ISO Compliance
Apply retention policies.
Control external sharing.
Use sensitivity labels to classify and protect data.

4. Security Trimming
Search results and content visibility respect user permissions.

